content: I tried this out as an alternative to iTunes for my wife to move away from her iPod for fitness classes.  In a lot of ways, this is good but in a number of ways, it is beyond frustrating. I've emailed JRT about it, and they suggest I go through and include only the folders I want.  In my situation, that's very cumbersome.  While it does a good job of playing music, organization is another matter.   They really need to look at the library functions from a *customer's* perspective.

Hi Ed,

"there's no way to remove it without deleting the source file" isn't really true. As stated, you can just not scan the folder with that file. content: Justin/Chris, I love the app (see my previous review). A couple of questions: I've upgraded my phone from a Samsung Note 4 to the Note 8. I also upgraded the memory card from 128G to 256GB, primarily for more audio and video. I copied my audio and video directories over to the new removable Memory card. In doing so, i lost all my Playlists. After repopulating my playlists, which was incredibly slow (more on that later), I now am having trouble playing my music from the Playlists. I get a message to open Settings and toggle SL under the Sound option. Even after the reboot I get the same message to toggle the SL option. The Album plays perfectly through the Album view. Any thoughts on this?  About the populating of the playlists, is there any way I can go to the Album (song) view and select multiple albums to add to or create a new playlist instead of doing it an album at a time or a song at a time?  Last, to re-request an option to rewind back 10 seconds and skip forward 30 seconds for audio recordings? Presently it's only moving the slider up and down and quite arbitrary.   I still love the app was much as I did when I first got it several years ago. Keep up the awesome work!! Thanks!!
replyContent:
Hi Dan, 

Open Rocket Player, then go to "Menu - Settings - Sound - Open SL". Once there, what we want to do is reverse whatever the current setting is, then reboot your device, then try playing again. 

Email me at MusicPlayer@JRTStudio.com I can answer all of these questions for you. My responses are character limited. 
-Chris

content: By far the best music player out there. Very simple but effective design where I can choose exactly the layout I need.  Also the gapless playback is just what I need. Thank you much for the work you put in this app!  (problem now solved) BUT I can't select an folder from external sdcard, it doesn't add the songs (rescan stops immediately). I think it's because your app doesn't ask for permission to have access/modify data for the permission manager (like for example file explorer) .  Happened since I flashed to android 7.  Phone is a rooted galaxy S4 with Android 7.1.2  Edit:  sadly reinstalling did not the job, the permission manager asked correctly for access, but still no import from sdcard. I post this so if somebody has a similar problem can find the solution.   Thank you for your fast reply and support!  You do an amazing job, keep it up!

content: Outstanding! This is by far the best music player for Android I've used (and I've tried several!). If you liked using an iPod in the ‚Äò00s, but prefer Android over iPhone now in the ‚Äò10s, then Rocket Player and iSyncr are for you. You can continue using iTunes as your music library software on your PC -- iSyncr can read your iTunes music library files and sync playlists, artists, albums, and podcasts to your Android phone and Rocket Player.  The playlists can even be read by other music apps on your phone. Rocket Player is very powerful, well-designed, and has many good features. It's very easy to create new playlists (including programmable ‚Äúsmart‚Äù or ‚Äúlive‚Äù playlists) on the app and shuffle them.  And when you sync back to your PC, iTunes will see any new playlists you made on your phone and import them.  You can also designate any long audio file (like a lecture you recorded) on your phone as a ‚Äúpodcast,‚Äù which allows you to bookmark (or remember playback position) that file.  The premium version of Rocket Player will play high-end audio files like FLAC and Apple Lossless from HDTracks. The developers are very good about replying to tech support emails.  Get these apps!!!

content: This is a solid player that suffers from one main flaw and that is that when it is used in conjunction with JSync, it brings over titles and album art that Rocket Player is in fact unable to play due to Digital Rights Management copy protection. When I am in the car using Rocket Player to stream via a Bluetooth connection, the Rocket Player app just stops when it encounters a Protected AAC audio file in your playlist. It doesn't make visible an error to explain what is going on so it takes trial and error to figure out what the underlying issue may be. Meanwhile, when you hit the "play" button, nothing happens and it continues to sit there without playing music. The app should be designed to advance to the next playable track while running under a Bluetooth (hands-free) connection. Instead, I have to go from hands-free to manual advance (on screen), in order to bypass tracks that are present in name only but cannot actually playback. In addition, this app ‚Äî even when unlocked ‚Äî doesn't play AIFF audio files, of which a lot of my library also consists.
replyContent: Hi, iSyncr won't (or shouldn't) sync copy protected music. Please email us at iSyncr@JRTStudio.com so that we can assist with this.

content: I've been using the unlocked version of this app for around a year on my Samsung GS4, and later my GS5. It's one of the best players; it looks clean, has very customizable playlists, and has a pretty intuitive UI.   That being said, the paid version of this app seems far less stable than the free version. I've been having consistent problems, on both the phones that I've used it on, with album art and general performance. Whether using a third-party downloader for art, or the in-app function, album art regularly fails to display. Sometimes it works, but more often album art doesn't display properly.   In addition, the paid app crashes regularly. I'd say that it crashes (becomes unresponsive and eventually closes itself) 1-2 times per day for me. Aside from the crashing, the app often 'lags', especially when changing songs. This process should be pretty seamless on an SGS5, but for some reason the lag is a constant annoyance.   The lock screen controls disappear too, but I think that's an issue with my device, rather than the app itself.
replyContent: We're sorry to hear that Mike. We'd love to fix these bugs within the application. Would you please email us at MusicPlayer@JRTStudio.com so that we can look into this with you?

Great app when you want it, but the app will never shut off. swipe it off, and next time the tablet is turned on it comes back playing what it was last playing. like sartre's hell, there's no exit.  ETA: JRTStudios replied to this by man-splaining to me that Android apps typically don't have exit/quit options like PCs or Macs.  Traditionally, also, however, when you "swipe away" an app to close it, it doesn't open back up every time you wake your device. Only Settings -> Force Quit works.
replyContent:
Sorry to hear that we're having problems closing the application. Android applications do not have a typical 'close/quit' option like traditional PC/Mac applications. Here's more information on why we do not have this option on our blog. 
http://www.jrtstudio.com/blog/Where-Is-Quit-Exit-Button-In-Rocket-Player. Email support for more info.

content: Simply Fantastic!  Truly a premium player for my Samsung Note 3 ... wow!	After considerable research of the many alternatives out there, very happy to report that my decision to give JRTStudio's  iSyncr  + Rocket Player Premium Unlocker  a go was totally worth every penny (all  798 of them). replyContent:
Hi Jeremy,

At this time, Rocket Player uses the Android Media Database for playlists. Why? Because then your playlists can be shared with other music players. Unfortunately, the Android Media Database does not support videos in playlists.

My choice is to support sharing, or support video playlists. Not both.

-Justin

Hi Willie,

I'm glad you like the player! If you select a song in a playlist and hold down on it, you can select "Play 1" to play just that song. Does that help you do accomplish what you are trying to do? Or do you want to move to the next song in the playlist after each finish, but manually? Email musicplayer@jrtstudio.com to let us know.
-Justin

If you want to sync music, playlists and ratings with Itunes then this is the player for you. I have tried Double Twist but DT does not sync the ratings from your device back to Itunes. Rocket player with iSyncr will do all that plus play counts ect- and it is fast and seamless. The player itself is slick and stylish. I have bought both Player Pro and Power Amp, both nice players. However, Power Amp does not sync so you can keep your music free of duplicates and stop wasting time trying to fix such issues. Player pro interface, while attractive, is not as practical as Rocket (i connect my Galaxy S3 to the Aux in my car radio but find the Player pro interface difficult to operate when driving- ratings is too close to the forward button on the widget and full screen). As for other owners of Galaxy S3's saying the sound is terrible- turn auto-haptic off. Overall, I have spent time and money on finding the best system for me to run from desktop to mobile and have concluded that isyncr + rocket player Premium ( can cross-fade and play more forms of files) to not only work seamlessly, but to be bristling with functionality while looking still incredibly stylish.

Easy to fix!  It seems that the Galaxy S3 has "Auto Haptic" that gives unlocker users a terrible distorted experience. Unfortunately, Samsung turns this setting on by default without asking users.  Try going to "Settings" > "Sound and Effects" > "Auto Haptic" > "Off"   Then try to play again with the unlocker.   Works like a charm!

Go to Phone Settings, Sound and turn Auto Haptic off. The playback will be fine immediately. Auto Haptic  can be also turned off only specifically per app by tapping the setting name. I hope developer could make Auto Haptic off by default for this app.

I bought this for the seamless integration with iSyncr, and also to support (financially) the developer(s). There are definitely a few refinements Rocket could use, though. Off the top of my head:  1. Find a way (similar to what Juice Defender and Tasker do) to have the option to always stay in the foreground. Sometimes after about twenty minutes of playing, Rocket will fall off the lockscreen controls.  2. There seems to be a slight delay switching from one song to the next when pressing the next button from the notifications dropdown.  3. It'd be great for shuffle to actually be shuffle and not random; that is, taking everything in the playlist and putting it in a random order instead of playing songs randomly (which means certain songs may repeat before another song is played).  If the iSyncr development is any indication, I'm expecting great things from Rocket in the future.
